![critical](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/critical.svg)

To prevent silent propagation of corrupt data and system desynchronization, we should add a runtime assertion (`assert!`) to verify that the calculated floating-point values for `ballistic.velocity` and `pos` are finite (not NaN or Inf). This ensures defensive programming and loud failures with diagnostic context if any non-finite values are introduced during the stop-drop calculation.

```rust
                    let proj = (effective[0] * nx + effective[1] * ny) / norm_xy_sq;
                    ballistic.velocity[0] = effective[0] - proj * nx;
                    ballistic.velocity[1] = effective[1] - proj * ny;
                    let inv_norm = 1.0 / norm_xy_sq.sqrt();
                    let nudge = AGENT_CAPSULE_RADIUS + WALL_EXTERIOR_NUDGE_M;
                    pos.x = contact.hit_x + nx * inv_norm * nudge;
                    pos.y = contact.hit_y + ny * inv_norm * nudge;
                    assert!(
                        ballistic.velocity[0].is_finite()
                            && ballistic.velocity[1].is_finite()
                            && pos.x.is_finite()
                            && pos.y.is_finite(),
                        "ballistic_integration_system stop-drop: non-finite values calculated. ballistic.velocity=[{}, {}], pos=[{}, {}], inputs: effective={:?}, normal=[{}, {}], hit=[{}, {}]",
                        ballistic.velocity[0],
                        ballistic.velocity[1],
                        pos.x,
                        pos.y,
                        effective,
                        nx,
                        ny,
                        contact.hit_x,
                        contact.hit_y
                    );
                    vel.dx = ballistic.velocity[0];
                    vel.dy = ballistic.velocity[1];
                    commands.entity(entity).remove::<ImpulseVelocity>();
                    continue;
```

