![high](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/high-priority.svg)

The comment states that the `origin` of the `DamageEvent` should represent the wall-face impact point rather than the post-step penetrated `*pos` to prevent decals from rendering buried inside the wall. However, `contact.hit_x` and `contact.hit_y` represent the capsule's center at the time of impact, which is `AGENT_CAPSULE_RADIUS` (0.3m) away from the actual wall face. This discrepancy will cause splat decals/effects to render floating in the air.

To align with the comment's intent, we should compute `inv_norm` earlier and subtract the normal vector scaled by the capsule radius from the capsule center to find the exact wall-face impact point. This also allows us to reuse `inv_norm` in the stop-drop branch, avoiding redundant calculations.

Additionally, in accordance with the repository rule for simulation code, we must use runtime assertions (`assert!`) to verify that floating-point calculations (such as `inv_norm`, `proj`, and the resulting coordinates/velocities) result in finite values (not NaN or Inf) to prevent silent propagation of corrupt data. The diagnostic messages should capture the raw input values.

```rust
                if norm_xy_sq >= WALL_NORMAL_DEGENERATE_EPSILON_SQ {
                    let inv_norm = 1.0 / norm_xy_sq.sqrt();
                    assert!(
                        inv_norm.is_finite(),
                        "inv_norm is not finite! norm_xy_sq: {}",
                        norm_xy_sq
                    );
                    // Splat gate (pure wall_face_splats): horizontal into-face
                    // speed >= WALL_SPLAT_SPEED, sign-clamped and non-unit-
                    // normal-correct. (norm_xy_sq is recomputed inside; we
                    // already know it is non-degenerate in this branch.)
                    if wall_face_splats(effective[0], effective[1], nx, ny) {
                        // SPLAT (hard impact -> kill). A corpse despawns
                        // directly; a live agent gets the forced-terminal-
                        // despawn sentinel DamageEvent (the same shape the
                        // kill-plane uses) so the resolver despawns it next tick
                        // (schedule .after). Keep BallisticMode + continue;
                        // the splat position is moot (gone next tick).
                        if dead.is_some() {
                            despawn_ballistic_corpse(
                                &mut commands,
                                &mut rapier,
                                entity,
                                agent_handle,
                            );
                            continue;
                        }
                        let origin_x = contact.hit_x - nx * inv_norm * AGENT_CAPSULE_RADIUS;
                        let origin_y = contact.hit_y - ny * inv_norm * AGENT_CAPSULE_RADIUS;
                        assert!(
                            origin_x.is_finite() && origin_y.is_finite(),
                            "DamageEvent origin is not finite! hit_x: {}, hit_y: {}, nx: {}, ny: {}, inv_norm: {}",
                            contact.hit_x,
                            contact.hit_y,
                            nx,
                            ny,
                            inv_norm
                        );
                        events.write(DamageEvent {
                            raw_amount: f32::MAX,
                            damage_type: DamageType::Physical,
                            target: entity,
                            impulse_magnitude: 0.0,
                            impulse_direction: [0.0, 0.0, 0.0],
                            // Origin = the wall-face impact point, not the post-
                            // step penetrated *pos (which sits inside the
                            // collider), so any future splat decal/effect renders
                            // on the face, not buried in the wall (GCA round-2).
                            origin: WorldPosition {
                                x: origin_x,
                                y: origin_y,
                                ..*pos
                            },
                            source: None,
                        });
                        continue;
                    }
                    // STOP-DROP (inelastic absorption). Project the into-face
                    // component out of effective (division by norm_xy_sq handles a non-unit
                    // 2D normal) into ballistic.velocity.xy; REMOVE
                    // ImpulseVelocity, else its decay next tick exposes a
                    // stored negative counter-component and flings the survivor
                    // backwards off the wall. Place the body on the wall EXTERIOR
                    // (contact point + unit-normal * (radius + epsilon)) so it falls
                    // OUTSIDE the enclosure even if the tick started penetrating.
                    // Vertical (gravity, in ballistic.velocity[2]) is
                    // untouched. No rejection increment - disposed, not counted.
                    let proj = (effective[0] * nx + effective[1] * ny) / norm_xy_sq;
                    assert!(
                        proj.is_finite(),
                        "proj is not finite! effective: {:?}, nx: {}, ny: {}, norm_xy_sq: {}",
                        effective,
                        nx,
                        ny,
                        norm_xy_sq
                    );
                    let vel_x = effective[0] - proj * nx;
                    let vel_y = effective[1] - proj * ny;
                    assert!(
                        vel_x.is_finite() && vel_y.is_finite(),
                        "ballistic velocity is not finite! effective: {:?}, proj: {}, nx: {}, ny: {}",
                        effective,
                        proj,
                        nx,
                        ny
                    );
                    ballistic.velocity[0] = vel_x;
                    ballistic.velocity[1] = vel_y;
                    // contact.hit_x/y is the capsule CENTER at the CCD
                    // contact - for a penetrating contact it already sits so the
                    // capsule SURFACE is on the wall face (the walkable-landing
                    // branch likewise sets pos.x = contact.hit_x directly).
                    // Nudge the center outward by WALL_EXTERIOR_NUDGE_M ONLY;
                    // adding the capsule radius again would double-count it and
                    // fling the body a radius too far (Greptile round-1 P1).
                    let new_pos_x = contact.hit_x + nx * inv_norm * WALL_EXTERIOR_NUDGE_M;
                    let new_pos_y = contact.hit_y + ny * inv_norm * WALL_EXTERIOR_NUDGE_M;
                    assert!(
                        new_pos_x.is_finite() && new_pos_y.is_finite(),
                        "new pos is not finite! hit_x: {}, hit_y: {}, nx: {}, ny: {}, inv_norm: {}",
                        contact.hit_x,
                        contact.hit_y,
                        nx,
                        ny,
                        inv_norm
                    );
                    pos.x = new_pos_x;
                    pos.y = new_pos_y;
