If a git hook file already exists but lacks execute permissions, Git will silently ignore it on Unix-like systems. The installer currently only sets the `0o755` mode when creating a *new* hook file. If the hook file already exists (e.g., created by another tool or editor), it is not made executable, which can lead to silent bypasses of the pre-push gate.

To prevent this, unconditionally ensure the hook file is executable by calling `fs.chmodSync(hookFile, 0o755)` (wrapped in a `try/catch` block for cross-platform safety).

```
    if (!fs.existsSync(hookFile)) {
      fs.mkdirSync(path.dirname(hookFile), { recursive: true });
      fs.writeFileSync(hookFile, '#!/bin/sh\n', { mode: 0o755 });
    }
    try {
      fs.chmodSync(hookFile, 0o755);
    } catch (err) {
      // Non-fatal fallback for restricted environments
    }
```

